title: Appeal a decision about a tree preservation order

heading_context: Appeal a decision about a tree preservation order
chunks.html_content:
Your council makes decisions about work on trees protected by preservation orders.

You can appeal if you applied to cut down or carry out work on a protected tree and:

  • you disagree with the decision
  • a decision was not made within 8 weeks

You can also appeal if you disagree with a tree replacement notice you’ve been given.

There’s no fee for appealing.

You must appeal:

  • within 28 days of the date on the council’s decision notice
  • before the date the tree replacement notice comes into effect

There’s no deadline if you’re appealing because your application was not decided within 8 weeks.

heading_context: Appeal a decision about a tree preservation order
chunks.html_content:
Fill in a tree preservation order appeal form or a tree replacement notice appeal form.

You also need:

  • a copy of the council’s decision or notice
  • any other documents that directly support your appeal

Email or post these documents with your completed appeal form to the council who made the decision and the Planning Inspectorate.

heading_context: Appeal a decision about a tree preservation order
chunks.html_content:
The Planning Inspectorate will check your appeal to make sure it’s valid. They’ll tell you what happens next and how long your appeal may take.

Their decision about your appeal will be based on:

  • the information you send
  • a site visit
  • your council’s documents, for example the tree preservation order

Your case officer will write to you if they need more information.

You’ll normally get a decision within 27 weeks.

The council may decide to contact anyone who commented on your original application (‘interested parties’). Your case officer will consider the statements any interested parties made.

Interested parties cannot make any further comments during the appeal but can withdraw their original statement.

heading_context: Appeal a decision about a tree preservation order
chunks.html_content:
You can apply for an ‘award of costs’ if anyone involved in your appeal has cost you money by behaving unreasonably, for example missing deadlines. However, you might have to pay another party’s costs too.

You can complain about how the Planning Inspectorate handled your appeal. There’s no time limit for complaints.

heading_context: Appeal a decision about a tree preservation order
chunks.html_content:
You can challenge the decision in the High Court if you think the Planning Inspectorate made a legal mistake.

Get advice from a lawyer if you’re unsure about this.
